The orchestration problem, and what docker alone doesn't solve.

You finished the docker course, so you can already do a lot. You can build images, run containers, mount volumes, wire up networks, and bring up a small stack with docker compose. So what is missing?

The honest answer is this. As soon as you have more than one machine, and more than one application, you run into a whole cluster of problems that docker alone was never designed to solve. Let's walk through them.

First, placement. Say you have five nodes and twenty containers to run. Which container goes on which node? You probably want the processor-hungry workloads spread out, and the small ones packed tightly together. Doing that by hand is a full time job. The kubernetes scheduler does it automatically.

Second, self healing. A container crashes at three in the morning. With docker alone, it stays crashed until a human notices. Kubernetes notices in seconds and starts a replacement. And if a whole node dies, kubernetes redistributes its containers onto the survivors.

Third, scaling. You launched two copies of your api, then traffic doubles and you need ten. With docker run, that means logging into machines and running commands by hand. With kubernetes you change one number, replicas equals ten, and the cluster converges to match.

Fourth, rollouts and rollbacks. Shipping version two of your service should not mean stopping all of version one and then starting all of version two. Kubernetes does rolling updates. It starts a version two, waits until it is healthy, stops a version one, and repeats. If version two misbehaves, one command rolls everything back.

Fifth, service discovery. Two containers might both be your api, with different random names. When the web pod wants to call the api, it should not have to know which specific pods exist right now. Kubernetes gives every workload a stable service name, like api, and cluster dee-en-ess does the rest.

And sixth, configuration and secrets. Twenty services need the same database address, and one of them needs a tee-el-ess certificate. Kubernetes has first class config maps and secrets that pods reference declaratively.

Here is the key insight. Docker still does the actual container work. Kubernetes is what you put on top, once you have more containers than you can supervise personally. On our platform map, this whole list lives inside the cluster box. The control plane is the machinery that solves placement, healing, scaling, and rollout, while the worker nodes run the pods it schedules.
